  "school": "Price Action",
  "definition": "A swing high is a price peak with lower highs on both sides; a swing low is a trough with higher lows on both sides. These structural pivots define market structure and trend, serve as liquidity areas (buyside above highs, sellside below lows), and are essential for identifying reversals and directional bias.",
  "identification_rules": [
    "A swing low is a candle with a low higher than both immediate left and right lows; a swing high is a candle with a high lower than both immediate left and right highs.",
    "If only one side exists (no right candle), it is not a confirmed swing; wait one more candle.",
    "Require clear separation from adjacent swings; swings too close to a prior swing of the same type are failure swings and not relevant. When multiple stacked swings lack separation, only the extreme is relevant.",
    "In an uptrend, successive swing highs must be higher than the prior swing high, and swing lows higher than the prior swing low. In a downtrend, they must be lower.",
    "Restrict look-back to three higher-time-frame candles including the current one to determine relevant swings. Prioritize swings aligning with higher-time-frame highs/lows.",
    "Validate the swing with a change in state of delivery (price closes through opposing candles that formed the swing) and SMT divergence against a correlated asset for reliability.",
    "Confirm the swing via a candle 2 closure (the candle sweeps the prior extreme and closes back inside the prior range) or a candle 3 closure (candle 3 closes beyond the body of candle 2 after candle 2 fails to close back inside).",
    "The swing must form at a valid point of interest (fair value gap, internal/external range liquidity, manipulation range) to be considered actionable.",
    "The swing candle itself should display a reversal OHLC sequence: bullish swings show open–low–high–close; bearish swings show open–high–low–close.",
    "After the swing forms, mark 50% of the swing candle's range (equilibrium) as a level for anticipating continuation in the following candle.",
    "On a weekly profile, a daily swing point on the reversal day (e.g., Wednesday) confirms the weekly high or low has formed.",
    "Mark the most recent unviolated swing high and swing low on the working time frame to define the current range boundaries.",
    "Apply fractally: the same closure-plus-CISD logic identifies swing points on any time frame pair.",
    "Compare swing points across correlated assets to gauge relative strength: a higher high on one asset while the other fails signals relative strength.",
    "Identify the most obvious swing high/low on the outer edge of the price range, ignoring internal secondary swings."
  ],
  "trading_implication": "Swing points define market structure and trend direction; they serve as anchors for bias and targets for reactions. A breakout beyond a swing with displacement signals a structural shift/reversal. Swing levels represent liquidity zones (buyside above highs, sellside below lows) that price often sweeps before reversing. Stops are placed beyond the swing, with entries taken back toward opposite relevant swings, aligned across timeframes. Target at least 2R toward drawn liquidity (prior swing highs/lows, failure swings).",
  "common_mistakes": [
    "Treating an unconfirmed swing (candle 3 with no candle on the right) as a valid point, or assuming a trend change before a confirmed swing high/low forms.",
    "Treating a swing too close to a prior high/low as relevant, ignoring the need for valid separation and risking early takeout.",
    "Looking for reversals at random swing points rather than restricting analysis to the three-higher-time-frame-candle look-back.",
    "Trying to short away from a high while leaving stacked failure swings above it, or going long with failure swings stacked below.",
    "Anticipating a reversal at an intermediate swing before price has reached the actual relevant extreme.",
    "Expecting continuation from deep retracements below the candle 3 equilibrium, ignoring that expansions should not give deep retracements (this signals reversal/consolidation).",
    "Expecting a swing to hold without additional confirmation such as change in state of delivery or SMT divergence.",
    "Interpreting a lower-timeframe break of a swing low as a full trend reversal without confirming alignment with the higher-timeframe trend.",
    "Failing to account for displacement; relying on wicks rather than a candle close beyond the swing point, which may represent liquidity grabs not structural shifts.",
    "Trading away from a level or entering continuation before a confirmed swing point has formed (anticipating reversal too early).",
    "Acting on a swing point based only on higher time frame closure without lower time frame CISD confirmation.",
    "Treating a wick or incomplete closure (no candle 2 closure) as a confirmed swing point, or entering candle 3 without prior candle 2 reversal signs.",
    "Using a swing point without pairing it to a valid point of interest (fair value gap, liquidity level) or without SMT confirmation.",
    "Expecting every swing point to be perfect or always hold; swing points can fail and market structure can be messy.",
    "Confusing a large-wick expansion candle with a valid reversal swing candle (e.g., treating a bearish open-high-low-close as a bullish reversal).",
    "Entering directly on the CISD rather than waiting for a continuation order block.",
    "Relying solely on lower time frame swing points without higher time frame context, leading to noisy signals.",
    "Treating a wick through a swing that closes back inside as a break, instead of recognizing it as a failure to displace (liquidity sweep).",
    "Treating failure swings (unconfirmed swings during expansion) as protected swing points.",
    "Mistaking a retracement that falls short of a prior swing for a reversal swing point.",
    "Ignoring SMT divergences between correlated assets at swing points, missing reversal signals.",
    "Evaluating relative strength solely by swing highs/lows without considering candle closures and relative candle sizes.",
    "Confusing external range liquidity (swing extremes) with internal range liquidity (FVG), leading to incorrect target setting.",
    "Expecting price to always cycle perfectly between internal and external liquidity, ignoring that markets sometimes skip levels or fail to retest.",
    "Applying the concept on a single timeframe without considering multi-timeframe hierarchy.",
    "Trading liquidity sweeps without a strong directional bias, ignoring that liquidity may have been cleared.",
    "Not waiting for a change in state of delivery (CSD) confirmation before entry, leading to inducement.",
    "Incorrectly identifying swing highs/lows, using invalid external liquidity levels as targets.",
    "Marking swing points before the right side confirmation is formed (i.e., before a lower high or higher low appears), resulting in invalid identification.",
    "Confusing internal secondary swings with the most obvious outer edge swings; prioritize the outer edge significant highs/lows."
  ],
